				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{VCF}}_i^{{\mathrm{im}}}$$\end{document}</tex-math><mml:math id="M18"><mml:msubsup><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">VCF</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi>i</mml:mi></mml:mrow><mml:mrow><mml:mi mathvariant="normal">im</mml:mi></mml:mrow></mml:msubsup></mml:math><inline-graphic xlink:href="41467_2019_13757_Article_IEq3.gif"/></alternatives></inline-formula> represents the life-cycle carbon emissions embodied in upstream production of products imported to Sector <italic>i</italic>; <italic>X</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> is the total output of sector <italic>i</italic>, <bold><italic>y</italic></bold><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> is the urban final demand; <italic>k</italic><sub><italic>i</italic></sub> is the carbon intensity of import to sector <italic>i</italic>; (<bold>I&#x02212;A</bold>)<sup><italic>&#x02212;1</italic></sup> is the Leontief inverse matrix, in which <bold>A</bold> represents the technical (input) coefficients of the urban economy, and <bold>I</bold> is the identity matrix; VCF<sub><italic>i</italic></sub><sup>fd</sup> represents the virtual emissions of sector <italic>i</italic> that can be&#x000a0;allocated to different categories of urban final demand, they are local (household and government) consumption <inline-formula id="IEq4"><alternatives><tex-math id="M19">\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
